The net present value is an indicator of a project's worth. It allows analysts to determine whether a certain project or firm is profitable based on the cashflow as well as other factors. In order to solve this, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Net present value}&=\dfrac{\text{Year 1 Cashflow}}{(1+\text{Required return})^1}+\dfrac{\text{Year 2 Cashflow}}{(1+\text{Required return})^2}\\
&+\dfrac{\text{Year 3 Cashflow}}{(1+\text{Required return})^3}+\dfrac{\text{Year 4 Cashflow}}{(1+\text{Required return})^4}\\
&-\text{Initial cashflow}
\end{aligned}$$
